{
  "answer": "In Allama Iqbal's poem \"Insaan\" (\"Man\") from *Bang-e-Dara Part 2*, the human being is portrayed as a unique enigma created by a \"strange tyranny\" of divine artistry: restless, self-alienated, and burdened by unquenchable thirst for knowledge amid life's insoluble mysteries.[^1] Unlike elements of nature—which find harmony, joy, and fulfillment in their destined motions and states (e.g., the river surging to the ocean, wind carrying clouds, stars bound in heavenly orbits, or the sun rising and setting in pious rhythm)—human existence is marked by isolation, sorrow, and bitterness, with no one to share its pain.[^2][^3]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, ch. 14 (\"Insaan\"), translation, [paragraphs](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/14-insaan/translation/#p-d7ec8e).\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, ch. 14 (\"Insaan\"), translation, [paragraphs](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/14-insaan/translation/#p-ad335e).\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, ch. 14 (\"Insaan\"), translation, [paragraphs](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/14-insaan/translation/#p-62d764).",
